"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-voices-of-nature-review-calls-of-the-wild-cfaa4c38?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">《自然之声》评论：野性的呼唤</a></h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-voices-of-nature-review-calls-of-the-wild-cfaa4c38"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821085?width=700&amp;height=445" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">阿尔多·白兰度/盖蒂图片社</span></div></div></div><p>动物可能没有接近人类语言的语言，但它们的哭声、咕噜声、嚎叫和吱吱声往往意义非凡。<em>大卫·巴拉什 (David P. Barash) 评论</em></p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-voices-of-nature-review-calls-of-the-wild-cfaa4c38?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-the-changing-world-order-1e9b0a30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">五本最佳书籍：关于不断变化的世界秩序的书籍</a></h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-the-changing-world-order-1e9b0a30"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820766?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">布伦特·基利克/法新社</span></div></div></div><p>由《普京对乌克兰的战争：俄罗斯的全球反革命运动》一书的作者塞缪尔·拉马尼 (Samuel Ramani) 选择。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-the-changing-world-order-1e9b0a30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读文章</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p><em>将精彩的阅读推荐发送到您的收件箱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=410&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">订阅</a>每周的图书时事通讯。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 19:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e<category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tony Bennett’s Heart Was in Jazz]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位于周五去世的歌手在长达 7 年的职业生涯中赢得了 19 项格莱美奖，并始终忠于自己对美国歌曲集的诠释，将音乐推向新的高度，并通过与 Lady Gaga 等艺术家的合作找到了新的听众。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10247095445958823342004587257712744812038"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10247095445958823342004587257712744812038"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">马克·迈尔斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 2:53 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tony-bennetts-heart-was-in-jazz-4ee11d48"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821598?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1976 年，托尼·贝内特 (Tony Bennett) 在伦敦 Palladium 剧院</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·雷德芬/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周五去世，享年 96 岁的托尼·贝内特 (Tony Bennett) 从来不喜欢被称为流行歌手。相反，他认为自己是“美国歌曲集的爵士乐诠释者”。他对摇滚乐的蔑视有时阻碍了他的职业生涯，尤其是在 20 世纪 60 年代末和 70 年代，当时他正处于谷底。但在 1986 年，60 岁的贝内特先生发起了音乐史上最引人注目、最持久的后期复出之一。</p><p>在他七十年的职业生涯中，贝内特先生的声音充满了歌剧般的乐观主义的阳光。他发行了100多张专辑和80多首单曲，获得19项格莱美奖（其中17项是1990年以后）并获得格莱美终身成就奖。从 1951 年他的第一张冠军单曲《Because of You》到 2021 年他与 Lady Gaga 合作的第二张专辑《Love for Sale》，Bennett 先生的声音风格通常会带来胜利的结局，此时他的力量和即兴技巧结合在一起，达到令人愉悦的渐强。</p><p>贝内特先生从未动摇过他爵士乐、健谈的街头歌手风格，即使在 1986 年回到哥伦比亚并发行了《The Art of Excellence》之后也是如此。随后该厂牌推出了一长串专辑，到 2010 年代，Bennett 先生已成为仍在工作的最年长的前摇滚明星，并成为年轻听众的父亲形象，这在很大程度上要归功于他与 Lady Gaga 的合作。</p><p>两人于 2014 年发行了《Cheek to Cheek》，该专辑赢得了格莱美奖，并进行了电视特别节目和全球巡演。虽然这次合并给 Lady Gaga 带来了老派的声望和一位传奇导师，但贝内特先生最终得到了更好的交易。 Gaga 台上台下的溺爱和女儿般的赞美使他再次成为超级巨星。</p><p> 2014 年，当我为《华尔街日报》采访贝内特先生时，我问他是否担心这次合作可能会被认为是卖光了。 “我的梦想是让爵士乐走出去，这样它就不会被遗忘，”他回答道。对于已经经历过国际明星经历的贝内特先生来说，让数百万年轻听众接触摇摆乐和爵士乐更令人满意。他有宿怨要算。</p><p>贝内特先生出生于 1926 年，在大萧条时期在纽约皇后区阿斯托里亚社区长大，在家唱歌、画画。在他 10 岁时父亲去世后，他的大家庭鼓励他进行艺术创作。一位艺术老师建议他继续唱歌，以防万一。</p><p>第二次世界大战期间参军后，他的歌唱生涯于 20 世纪 40 年代末在纽约的俱乐部开始。回到纽约后，他自称乔·巴里 (Joe Bari)，经常光顾爵士音乐家的聚会场所。</p><p> 1949 年，珀尔·贝利 (Pearl Bailey) 邀请贝内特先生在格林威治村的一家俱乐部为她开场，并敦促鲍勃·霍普 (Bob Hope) 来见他。霍普带着贝内特先生上路，把他的姓氏从贝内代托缩短为贝内特。 1950 年，贝内特先生与哥伦比亚唱片公司签约。</p><p>在 20 世纪 50 年代，他录制了几张爵士乐风格的专辑，其中最著名的是与吉他手 Chuck Wayne 合作的“Cloud 7”，以及与钢琴家 Ralph Sharon 合作的“The Beat of My Heart”</p>和领先的爵士打击乐手。 1962年，贝内特先生的《我把我的心留在了旧金山》在告示牌专辑排行榜上攀升至第五位，主打歌成为他的标志性歌曲。接下来是贝内特先生更喜欢的两张专辑——《I Wanna Be around》（1963 年）和《电影歌曲专辑》（1966 年）。<p></p><p>但 1964 年披头士乐队的到来和新一代摇滚歌手兼词曲作者的出现让美国歌曲集变得陈旧。 1967 年，具有摇滚精神的克莱夫·戴维斯 (Clive Davis) 接手哥伦比亚之后，贝内特先生面临着录制当代流行音乐的压力。 “有些歌曲让我身体不适，”贝内特在自传中说道。</p><p> 1972 年，贝内特一怒之下离开了哥伦比亚，随后他为小唱片公司录制的专辑均未能进入排行榜。在此期间，贝内特先生录制了两张专辑，他告诉我这是他职业生涯中最好的专辑——与爵士钢琴家比尔·埃文斯的二重唱唱片。</p><p> 70 年代末，贝内特先生陷入了困境。他吸食可卡因，四处寻找工作，还两次离婚。到 1979 年，贝内特先生已濒临破产。他情绪崩溃，向儿子丹尼和戴寻求帮助。他们还清了他的债务并开始重建他的职业生涯。</p><p>随后他的许多专辑都在 Billboard 200 排行榜上名列前茅，其中《Duets II》和《Cheek to Cheek》名列第一。他还与 Phil Woods、Wynton Marsalis 和 Bill Charlap 等爵士艺术家合作录制了专辑。 2001 年，Bennett 先生与妻子 Susan 创立了</p>纽约皇后区的弗兰克辛纳屈艺术学院是一所学生通过试镜入学的高中。<p></p><p> 《Duets II》是一个转折点。其中包括与艾米·怀恩豪斯 (Amy Winehouse) 合作的充满情感的《身体与灵魂》，艾米·怀恩豪斯在录制该歌曲后不久就去世了。 Bennett先生和Lady Gaga（Lady Gaga也出现在这张专辑中）在Lady Gaga获释后就开始讨论一起录制一张歌曲集标准的专辑。</p><p> 2018 年，我在班尼特先生的艺术工作室接受《华尔街日报》采访时，我问他为什么个人如此痴迷爵士乐。 “这让我保持诚实，”他轻声说道。 “这是一件自发的事情。你必须凭直觉唱歌，并希望那一刻是正确的。年轻人喜欢它。他们只需要知道他们有选择。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。迈尔斯是《为什么爵士乐会发生》和《Anatomy of 55 More Songs》（格罗夫出版社）的作者。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 18:53:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tony-bennetts-heart-was-in-jazz-4ee11d48</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tony-bennetts-heart-was-in-jazz-4ee11d48<category>艺术评论</category><category>奖项</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>托尼·贝内特</category><category>奖项</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The World Behind the World’ Review: What the Brain Scan Misses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>神经科学家的研究就好像思想和感觉的作用微乎其微。意识无法绘制其流动图。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11216831118178654471904590076432707316158"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821062?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Steven Siewert/悉尼先驱晨报/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11216831118178654471904590076432707316158"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">朱利安·巴吉尼</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日中午 12:02 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-behind-the-world-review-what-the-brain-scan-misses-6033e7ad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>想象一下，你可以将自己缩小到足以在大脑中旅行的程度。登上海马体或绕小脑航行无疑是一次很棒的体验，非常值得一游。但你在任何地方都无法体验有大脑的人在想什么、听什么或感觉什么。对你来说，有意识生命的嗡嗡作响的蜂巢只是细胞的集合。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/66a0226a-5841-4447-9fdf-b8e76f79cd70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>如此奇妙的旅程的局限性指向两种看似不可调和的看待我们自己的方式：作为生物物质和作为自我意识的心灵。这种对比几个世纪以来一直困扰着哲学家和科学家，有时会从客观与主观、外部与内部的角度来界定。神经科学家埃里克·霍尔（Erik Hoel）研究了人类自我感知的这两个领域，将它们称为外在观点和内在观点。在《世界背后的世界》一书中，他试图解释它们为何存在、我们如何尝试将它们纳入共识以及为什么我们可能永远不会完全成功。最重要的是，他试图反驳如今越来越频繁的论点，即神经元的放电（而不是思想和欲望）是人类行为的唯一真正原因。似乎这还不够，他试图用 200 多页的篇幅来保存我们也有自由意志的观点。他承认，他的项目“在范围上是不可能的”，但他仍然大胆地尝试一下。</p><p>霍尔先生首先挑战了这样一种观点，即内部和外部的双重视角是人类经验中长期不变的特征。相反，他认为内在的观点需要一段时间才能形成自己的观点。他说，自荷马时代以来，我们描述和表达内心世界的能力已经有了很大的发展。最早的骚动可以在古希腊作家身上看到，比如西蒙尼德斯，他开发了“记忆宫殿”的记忆方法，而欧里庇得斯则表达了他笔下人物的内心生活。霍尔先生说，这种观点在中世纪时期已经衰落，但在文艺复兴时期被塞万提斯等作家赋予了新的生命，并随着 18 世纪小说的兴起而得到进一步发展。</p><p>这个论点是推测性的，时间线太简洁了，但关键点是精心设计的：意识可能是人类的普遍性，但我们表达其品质并将其明确识别为独特视角的愿望和能力是人类变量，并不比我们科学地研究世界的能力更天生。事实上，霍尔先生说，科学的兴起也取决于我们学习一种观点——外在的观点。他以更快的速度简要介绍了这一发展过程。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 14 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>人类意识的挑战性科学、观察历史循环、奥尔曼兄弟的南方摇滚配方等等。</p></div></div><p>但随后，在这本书最有趣的一章中，霍尔先生改变了策略，认为神经科学的成就——外在自我审视的典型模式——远远低于炒作和头条新闻所暗示的。我们得到了如此多的承诺，仿佛对大脑细胞集合的仔细研究将为意识提供完整的解释。霍尔先生说，事实是，绘制大脑神经元活动图为我们提供的预测信息非常少。例如，你无法通过脑部扫描来可靠地判断某人是否患有抑郁症。大脑的可塑性太强，结构太不稳定，而且太复杂，扫描无法精确定位神经元水平上的作用以及任何特定的神经活动模式会产生什么影响。</p><p>但还有一个更深层次的问题。神经科学假设它可以纯粹通过采用外在的观点来进行。然而，正如我们假设的大脑周围的微型旅程所表明的那样，这种观点有严重的局限性——几乎从定义上来说，它排除了意识本身。神经科学家继续认为这种排除并不重要。霍尔先生写道，他们倾向于将意识视为“大脑的某种最小子系统，不拥有任何信息，几乎毫无用处。来自发动机的蒸汽。”霍尔先生认为，“我们作为一个有机体的生存”取决于意识及其准确跟踪现实的能力，或者用他的话说，取决于“始终真实且信息丰富的意识流”。他补充道，“除了意识之外”，大脑中没有任何东西是有意义的。</p><p>至此，霍尔先生巧妙地为另一场旋风之旅做好了准备，这一次调查了来自心理学和神经科学的意识理论。但这里的情况变得更加艰难。为了混合隐喻，读者面临着陡峭的学习曲线，即使在最好的情况下也很不稳定。霍尔先生开始使用逻辑真值表，就好像它们像条形图一样易于阅读，但这并没有帮助。</p><p>霍尔先生的主要研究方向是由神经科学家朱利奥·托诺尼 (Giulio Tononi) 开发的综合信息理论。粗略地说，它的中心论点是，物理系统整合信息的能力越强，它的意识就越强。这种整合（将不同信息元素组合在一起的能力）是通过标记为“phi”的单位来衡量的。该理论称，如果能够准确计算 phi，它就可以预测任何系统（人类、动物或机器）的意识水平。霍尔先生本人花了数年时间研究综合信息理论，但最终对此感到不满意。他认为，它可能描述了意识系统的某些关键特征，但它却无法解释意识本身。</p><p>霍尔先生得出了一个有些悲观的结论，即正如哥德尔表明数学或逻辑中没有任何形式系统可能是完整的一样，科学也许永远无法解释内在的观点。但读者并没有陷入这种低调。 《世界背后的世界》的最后几章捍卫了意识体验的作用。霍尔先生正在挑战那些坚持认为由于所有物理系统（我们也是其中之一）都无情地遵循因果规则，因此自由意志是一种幻觉的人。他的论点复杂而微妙，但本质上它等于一个简单的想法，即什么算作因果关系取决于规模。</p><p>例如，你无法通过分析大气中单个原子的运动来判断是否会下雨或刮飓风。你必须着眼于更大、更具包容性的尺度，即气压系统和云的形成。因为只有这个级别的事件才能解释和预测天气事件，所以我们正确地说它们是天气事件的原因。同样，单个神经元的放电模式并不能告诉你一个人将如何行动。但某人的想法和感受可能会这样做。霍尔先生说，这些心态被正确地称为行动原因：它们具有细胞所不具备的“能动性”。</p><p>霍尔先生似乎还没有承担足够的责任，他最后解决了自由意志这个棘手的问题。他的结论表明了这项任务的雄心：“拥有自由意志意味着成为在相关描述层面上因果出现的代理人，对他来说，最近的内部状态在因果上比遥远的过去状态更相关，并且在计算上是不可约的。”这是一个完全合理的建议，但它需要超过 13 页的篇幅才能清楚地表达其含义，更不用说为它建立一个案例了。</p><p> 《世界背后的世界》试图做得太多、太快，因此有时很难跟上，有时虽然有启发性，但并不真正有说服力。但它提供了一系列令人振奋的智力挑战，并且在其简洁的演示中，几乎看起来就像是一组至少六本你想读的其他书籍的戏弄散文预告片。霍尔先生还很年轻：他有时间和才华来写它们。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。巴吉尼是《重获自由：自由意志的可能性》一书的作者。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 16:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-behind-the-world-review-what-the-brain-scan-misses-6033e7ad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-world-behind-the-world-review-what-the-brain-scan-misses-6033e7ad<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Fourth Turning Is Here’ and ‘End Times’ Review: Big Wheel]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国历史的循环观是否预示着一场即将到来的政治危机——以及如何应对这场危机？ <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590095991034279562"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821120?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590095991034279562"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">多米尼克·格林</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 11:59 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fourth-turning-is-here-and-end-times-3439006b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>如果历史学家能够预测未来，他们的报酬就会更高。他们已经很难讲述过去了。历史不断被改写，因为不可能不从现在开始书写。预测是经济学家的事，但他们的学科令人失望的结果解释了为什么托马斯·卡莱尔称其为“令人沮丧的科学”。但那时，他是一位历史学家。</p><p>尼尔·豪（Neil Howe）和彼得·图尔钦（Peter Turchin）采用不同但具有启发性的方法来书写当前和不久的将来的预测性“大历史”。每个人都曾写过对未来进行过令人印象深刻的预测的书籍。两者都检测到我们经验的日常波动中的深层循环模式。两人都认为美国现在正陷入一场危机，其解决方案将在 2030 年代改变美国社会及其在世界上的地位。</p><p> 1997年，豪和威廉·施特劳斯出版了《第四次转折》，描述了英美历史上更新、稳定、衰落和危机的四代人循环。每一代“转变”大约需要20年，所以一个完整的周期大约需要80年。当前的周期始于 1946 年。豪和施特劳斯预测，其第四个转折点，即国内冲突的“危机”阶段，将在 2020 年左右达到高潮，然后在 2026 年左右通过经济重组成功解决。事实并非如此，但它足以表明历史周期理论的价值。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/6c46fec9-0736-4447-a333-fef0b333e840.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “旧的美利坚共和国正在崩溃，”豪先生在《第四次转折来了》中写道。豪先生的第四个转折，就像他的周期一样，包含子阶段。当前危机的“前兆”是 9/11 后的反恐战争。 “催化剂”是 2008 年的金融危机和随之而来的大衰退。第一次“重生”是2016年的选举，该选举将国家划分为“两个党派不可调和的阵营”。我们现在面临着“ekpyrosis”，这个术语源自斯多葛派哲学家的观点，即宇宙周期性地自我毁灭和重建。</p><p>正如建筑项目经常发生的那样，竣工时间被推迟。人们的寿命比之前的周期更长，因此 80 年的周期（豪先生称之为“saeculum”）可以延长至 92 年。这场危机的开始时间比预期要晚，结束时间也会更晚，“在 2030 年代中期的某个时候”。我们很快就会离开“破坏性阶段”，进入“建设性阶段”。这并不像听起来那样令人欢呼，因为建设性阶段也具有高度破坏性。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 14 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>人类意识的挑战性科学、观察历史循环、奥尔曼兄弟的南方摇滚配方等等。</p></div></div><p> “与外部侵略者进行全面斗争”和“内部政治革命或内战”的风险随着危机而达到顶峰。这些可能会导致国内彻底崩溃，就像过去一样（英国的玫瑰战争、美国内战）。或者，一个派系可以实现国内主导地位，并领导“一个统一的国家与外部敌人发生一场决定性的冲突”（伊丽莎白·英格兰对抗西班牙无敌舰队，罗斯福总统对抗轴心国）。第二次重生，“可能”通过选举，“可能”通过政党领导层的更迭，可以防止流血事件。但“无限期的僵局”将“打破历史格局”。</p><p>豪先生的理论以代际心理学和荣格原型为基础。艺术家一代的“敏感的年轻人”在第一次转折中成长，这是一个“加强机构的乐观时代”。在我们的社会中，这是杜鲁门、艾森豪威尔和肯尼迪总统以及沉默的一代（1925-42 年出生）的“美国高层”。第二次转折是一个“觉醒”，一个“精神剧变的激情时代”，先知一代的“挑衅的年轻十字军”用新的价值观挑战公民秩序。这就是始于 20 世纪 60 年代中期的意识革命，以婴儿潮一代（出生于 1943-60 年）为先知。</p><p>随着旧政权的衰弱和新价值观的扎根，第三次转折是个人主义、制度弱化和社会“瓦解”的时代。游牧一代（X 世代，生于 1961-81 年）是“异化的年轻人”，他们在文化战争和政治中心主义的崩溃中成长。第四次转折使他们成为应对危机的“务实的中年领导者”。他们为“英雄”一代和新的高度扫清了道路。最后的英雄是大兵一代（出生于 1901-24 年）；当前的英雄是千禧一代（1982-2005 年出生）。统治下一个美国的艺术家将是 Z 世代，或者豪先生所说的“家园者”。</p><p>豪预测婴儿潮一代的黄昏。 2029 年 4 月 13 日，以“埃及黑暗恶魔蛇”命名的大型小行星阿波菲斯将“距离地球非常危险，肉眼很容易就能看到”。倾向于“焦土政治”和“最后通牒和灾难的语言”的婴儿潮一代将拥抱“衰落和死亡的新道德”，并对眼前的一切征税。</p><p>作为“二战以来最尚武的老一辈”，他们会劝告年轻的美国人做出牺牲，但“他们要求的牺牲远远超过未来的回报”。年轻人会认为这是“无能，甚至是妄想”。只有X世代的游牧民族才能缓和“婴儿潮一代牧师战士”的求死热情，并阻止“一些正义的老水瓶座人”“把世界的灯熄灭”。</p><p>豪先生确定了这个过程及其情绪，但没有确定其原因或机制。 “英美”理想将会胜利，因为历史精神要求它。过去的英美危机“基本上得到了成功的解决”，因此美国人可能会期待一个“充满奇迹的世界”，他们的城市复兴，经济繁荣，出生率上升，美国引领“社会民主的全球生育主义改造”。但如果美国人不再认为自己属于“盎格鲁”社会呢？如果美国因大国冲突或“自我毁灭性内战”而“受到损害和削弱”，或者“其政治宪法急剧退化”怎么办？水晶球一片空白，前景严峻。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/0c7d2e59-bc45-4080-a017-23a0089318d2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>彼得·图尔钦 (Peter Turchin) 对理想主义、英美例外论或原型不太感兴趣。他在苏联长大，是一位受过训练的生物学家和一位数据处理专家。图尔钦先生在《末日：精英、反精英和政治瓦解之路》一书中提出了一种清晰而优雅的理论，该理论以自然法则和科学发现的方式跨越时间和地点而保持稳定。如果说豪先生的愿景充满了占星学的洛可可风格，那么图尔钦先生的愿景则具有社会科学的尖锐优雅。命运是数据流，而不是世代特征。他将其称为“cliodynamics”，以希腊历史缪斯克利奥（Clio）的名字命名。它可能发生在这里，因为它总是发生在任何地方。</p><p>对图尔钦来说，帝国和大国是“在一体化和瓦解阶段之间摆动的节拍器”。他只看到美国历史上政治两极分化的“两个大周期”。第一次是从 1830 年到 1930 年； 1920年左右的南北战争和劳工骚乱达到顶峰，1930年至1970年间贫富差距缩小的“大压缩”才得到解决。第二次两极分化始于1970年，贫富差距再次拉大，很快就会达到顶峰。贫富差距扩大是因为富有和人脉广泛的人为了自身利益而打开“财富泵”。社会学家称之为“寡头政治铁律”。这导致公众信任度下降、公共债务激增、实际工资价值下降以及对赞助的激烈竞争。</p><p>这种竞争武装了革命机制：“精英生产过剩”、“拥有高级学位的年轻毕业生生产过剩”。法国和俄国革命表明，“真正危险的革命者”是“失意的精英有志者”，尤其是律师。美国“越来越多的有资格的年轻人”“注定会成为受过教育的不稳定阶层”。他们“除了不稳定之外没有什么可失去的”，而且他们不会悄悄地“检查自己的特权”。想想#MeToo、“黑人的命也是命”、取消文化，以及社交媒体上对 JK 罗琳所谓的“变性恐惧症”进行的塞勒姆式的政治迫害。也许这就是莎士比亚写下“我们要做的第一件事，杀死所有律师”的原因。</p><p>图尔钦先生提出了一个三阶段的政治演变。在危机前，这个摇摇欲坠的国家面临着来自不同精英派系的多重挑战。在危机阶段，合法性的丧失会导致国家崩溃和精英内部争夺战利品的冲突。最终，“新的权力垄断”出现了。获胜者的重点是“获得对重建的政治、宗教和社会机构的常规接受”。我们“显然正处于从危机前到危机的过渡期”。</p><p>特朗普就任总统后，美国因“精英生产过剩和民众贫困”而处于“国家崩溃的边缘”。国家“面对众多反精英挑战者，从觉醒左派到新右派，努力维持对意识形态格局的控制”。他声称，当今美国的“结构状况”与其说是 20 世纪 70 年代的美国，不如说是“其他革命前的社会，例如 19 世纪末的俄罗斯”。正如俄罗斯革命者常说的，该怎么办？</p><p>十九世纪的英国通过移民、工业独创性以及最重要的将政治权力从地主士绅转移到“向上流动的商业精英”的制度改革，减轻了精英生产过剩和大规模贫困的压力。美国在进步时代“关闭了财富泵”，但在 20 世纪 70 年代却允许“自私精英”重新开启它。图尔钦警告说，解决这场危机需要“统治阶级具备一定的能力”。</p><p>未来总是不被书写的，但这并不意味着它不应该被书写。阅读先知书总是有好处的。豪先生的基于世代的计划可能看起来很奇怪，但回想起来，我们确实经常同意每一代人都有自己的性格。那么为什么不展望未来呢？ 《第四次转折来了》是宏大的历史和大胆的未来学，而且越贴近当下，就越显得合理。图尔钦先生既是一位过去主义者，也是一位未来主义者，他的理性方法让《末世》合理地确定了美国历史现在正在转向的一个枢纽。</p><p>这些书在方法和范围上如此不同，但却是相辅相成的。距离危机爆发还有大约十年的时间，所以有足够的时间阅读这两篇文章。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。格林是《期刊》撰稿人，也是皇家历史学会会员。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:59:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fourth-turning-is-here-and-end-times-3439006b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fourth-turning-is-here-and-end-times-3439006b<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>历史</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>历史</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Kings of Their Own Ocean’ Review: The Trouble With Tuna]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>海洋边界的建立是为了恢复蓝鳍金枪鱼的数量，将大西洋划分为截然不同的捕鱼区。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590087792939866272"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820744?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">地中海中，一群大西洋蓝鳍金枪鱼被渔网包围。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：anbusiello R/Alamy </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590087792939866272"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">理查德·亚当斯·凯里</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 11:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kings-of-their-own-ocean-review-the-trouble-with-tuna-97c98c24"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>鱼儿在水的掩护下，想去哪儿就去哪儿。他们一直这样做，令渔民以及最近那些负责计算海中鱼类并仅授予可持续捕捞许可的官僚、科学家和数学家感到懊恼。</p><p>世界上几乎 90% 的海洋渔业已经被充分开发或过度捕捞，说起来容易做起来难。每种鱼类都是其高风险故事中的参与者，但一些最好的故事都发生在那些愿意花高价购买海鲜的人所珍视的鱼类身上：例如，鲟鱼，其乳白色的卵可能会变成鱼子酱;或者是蓝鳍金枪鱼，其浓密的红色腹肉是最令人向往的寿司中必不可少的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/5a32cc7c-2e39-4c66-a921-e34a898d84e8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>金枪鱼有 15 种，但在凯伦·平钦 (Karen Pinchin) 的《他们自己的海洋之王：金枪鱼、痴迷和我们海洋的未来》中，焦点完全集中在大西洋蓝鳍金枪鱼身上，它是一种快速的温血掠食者，是一种生理奇迹，已知长度可达近 13 英尺，重量可达 1,500 磅。平钦女士是一名加拿大记者，她的叙述围绕着一条特殊的蓝鳍金枪鱼，一条名叫阿米莉亚的雌性蓝鳍金枪鱼，以及 2004 年 9 月的一天在罗德岛海峡抓住她、标记她并释放她的痴迷包租船船长。</p><p>这个故事的第三个维度是由蓝鳍金枪鱼捕捞国家联盟于 1981 年在水中绘制的一条线。这条锯齿形拉链位于大西洋中部（以西经 45 度左右为中心），旨在遏制 20 世纪 70 年代以寿司为主导的对该物种的过度捕捞，反映出这样一种信念，即大西洋东部和西部的蓝鳍金枪鱼由两个独立的种群组成，因此可以单独管理。 “一夜之间，这条概念线改变了大西洋蓝鳍金枪鱼的渔业，”平钦女士写道。 “在大西洋的欧洲一侧，收成仍然是混战，对于历史上在这些水域捕捞的国家来说，可以捕获和杀死多少鱼没有配额。对于北美来说，对于包括美国和加拿大在内的国家（以及出于历史原因的日本）来说，除了那些据称是为了‘科学目的’而捕获的鱼之外，没有任何一条鱼是可以合法捕获的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The challenging science of human consciousness, watching history&#39;s cycles, the Allman Brothers&#39; Southern rock recipe and more.</p></div></div><p> Europeans stood by their higher numbers for bluefins in the sea, and Japanese buyers schooled to the Mediterranean. Meanwhile, Rhode Island boat captain Al Anderson—who since his youth had been tagging fish to feed his own curiosity, and in so doing forged contacts and alliances in the scientific community—continued helping his charter clients catch bluefins on a catch-tag-and-release basis.</p><p> Ms. Pinchin writes acutely about the codependence between fisheries science and politics. The two-stock theory, in fact, never held much water. As early as 1976, an Anderson-tagged bluefin had been recaptured in Europe&#39;s Bay of Biscay. But in 1981, the theory provided the North American delegation a means to claim control of at least half the Atlantic bluefin harvest, and so provide a lifeline for the species, “given,” writes Ms. Pinchin, “European countries&#39; refusal to reduce their catches.”</p><p> The author tries to have it both ways in exalting the 2018 death of Amelia—by gunshot, in a Portuguese set net—along with the return of her “twisted, weathered tag” to the National Marine Fisheries Service as the evidence-based death knell of what was always merely a policy construct. But it makes for good storytelling, as well as a point of entry into Ms. Pinchin&#39;s deft portraits of such as the revered, if irascible, Capt. Anderson and his wife, Daryl. The policy debates of recent decades are personified in the public wrangling between the prominent ecologist Carl Safina, who argues for the most stringent protections for bluefins, and the scientist Molly Lutcavage, who scrabbles for grants, argues for less in the way of politics and more by way of hard science in bluefin policy, and who herself—in 2007—captured and tagged the peripatetic Amelia off Cape Cod.</p><p> There are other rich characters here as well, and fascinating excursions into the cul-de-sacs of this world, such as the annual bluefin sportfishing tournament that drew international anglers, celebrities and millions of dollars in today&#39;s money to two little towns in Nova Scotia—until the tuna disappeared in the 1970s. That was when a fish previously considered only marginally edible suddenly became a lucrative delicacy, and Ms. Pinchin deliciously describes the Rev. Sun Myung Moon&#39;s strenuous efforts to build a vertically integrated operation—boats, processors, distributors—that would corner the world&#39;s bluefin market for his Unification Church and make its founder, as Moon described himself then, “King of the Ocean.”</p><p> Some material feels like padding—do we need the speeches made at Capt. Anderson&#39;s induction into a game-fishing hall of fame?—while it seems an omission that a story as free-range as Amelia herself should not take stock of the growing bluefin farming industry, where some 15 pounds of mackerel and herring are required as feed to produce each pound of bluefin belly meat. Such hollowing out of the ocean&#39;s food chain portends to have something to do, I think, with “the future of our seas.”</p><p> In her final chapter, Ms. Pinchin ties her wide-angle, free-wheeling story together by recalling what she terms “butterfly-wing events”: small moments in the lives of her characters, little tricks of circumstance, that have played to momentous effect on the Atlantic bluefin and the hardscrabble fishing communities that have donned the “golden handcuffs” that come with temporary infusions of foreign cash. In the Portuguese villages near where Amelia was taken for sushi, this has meant criminal networks, cross-border smuggling and depleted waters.</p><p> Those butterfly-beats powerfully encapsulate the intimate interdependence of predator and prey, especially when human predators flatten a wild prey animal into an economic commodity and allow short-term self-interest—well, greed—to push predation past that invisible threshold between sustainability and a spiral to extinction. “Diving into the history of bluefin and the human communities that have lived alongside the species for millennia,” Ms. Pinchin writes, “I glimpsed a vision of a reciprocal future, one in which human passions could dovetail with our long-term survival on this planet—a quest that must include the right of wildlife to thrive alongside us.”</p><p> To that end, the author argues, we all need some version of that 45-degree line. Certainly we do, simply because we keep proving that we are—like Lucifer in the Rolling Stones&#39; “Sympathy for the Devil”—“in need of some restraint.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Carey&#39;s books include “Against the Tide: The Fate of the New England Fisherman” and “The Philosopher Fish: Sturgeon, Caviar, and the Geography of Desire.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kings-of-their-own-ocean-review-the-trouble-with-tuna-97c98c24</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kings-of-their-own-ocean-review-the-trouble-with-tuna-97c98c24<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>natural environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Brothers and Sisters’ Review: The Age of the Allman Brothers]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Even after the loss of two of their founding members, the Georgia-based band created a country-blues sound that captivated audiences. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093823843829384"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820679?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Gregg Allman, left, and Duane Allman, performing with the Allman Brothers Band on Boston Common in 1971.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Peter Tarnoff/MediaPunch/IPX/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093823843829384"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Gavin Edwards</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 11:36 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brothers-and-sisters-review-the-age-of-the-allmans-956e44a4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> “Anyone can boil a potato, but not everyone can make gravy,” said rock promoter Bill Graham on the day he died in 1991. He was praising the Allman Brothers Band, who blended country music, blues grooves and jazz flourishes with cornmeal-gravy guitar solos, establishing the recipe for both jam bands and what would come to be known as Southern rock. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/47ae2ecf-211b-4250-bbdb-73c72822a7ac.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The mythic figure at the center of the Allman Brothers was Duane Allman, the redheaded guitar genius who ignited the recording sessions for Eric Clapton&#39;s “Layla,” who played slide with an empty bottle of cold medication on his ring finger, and who led the band through epic improvisations on tracks like “Whipping Post.” The other founding members were Duane&#39;s younger brother, Gregg (nicknamed “PB” by his bandmates, short for “Pretty Boy”), on vocals and organ; guitarist Dickey Betts, whose first professional gig was playing music on a circus midway; Mr. Betts&#39;s buddy Berry Oakley on bass; and two drummers, the rock warrior Butch Trucks and the jazz philosopher Johnie Lee Johnson, aka Jaimoe. After their first jam session, Duane barred the door and told the other musicians: “Anybody in this room who&#39;s not going to play in my band, you&#39;ve got to fight your way out.”</p><p> Despite being based in Macon, Ga., the band disliked the term “Southern rock”: “All rock &#39;n&#39; roll came from the South; it is Southern by definition,” said Gregg Allman. “You might as well call it &#39;rock rock.&#39;” As they built their following, the band careened into every possible pitfall of music stardom, from addiction to toxic ego battles to disastrous business deals. Although the Allman Brothers broke up more than once, they persisted from 1969 to 2014, ultimately entering the Rock &amp; Roll Hall of Fame as haggard but respected elders.</p><p> The journalist Alan Paul devoted his 2012 oral history “One Way Out” to the band&#39;s early years. He has expanded his frame—even while focusing on the making of a single record—with “Brothers and Sisters: The Allman Brothers Band and the Inside Story of the Album That Defined the &#39;70s.”</p><p> “Brothers and Sisters” is nominally about the 1973 album of the same title, recorded after the deaths of Duane Allman and Oakley, both of whom were killed in motorcycle accidents one year apart. Although the LP spent five weeks at No. 1 and included the hit “Ramblin&#39; Man,” few people would call it the album that defined the decade, despite the overheated subtitle of this book. (Three nominations for LPs that arguably achieved that cultural impact: Fleetwood Mac&#39;s “Rumours”; the “Saturday Night Fever” soundtrack; and Stevie Wonder&#39;s “Songs in the Key of Life.”)</p><p> The band staggered on after those enormous losses, trying to honor Duane Allman&#39;s vision without replacing him on guitar. With Gregg Allman overwhelmed by grief and looking for solace in alcohol and drugs, Mr. Betts became leader of the band, which added Chuck Leavell on piano and Lamar Williams on bass. It&#39;s surprising that “Brothers and Sisters” was released at all—that it contains music as purely joyful as Mr. Betts&#39;s instrumental “Jessica” seems like a small miracle.</p><p> Mr. Paul&#39;s prose doesn&#39;t soar like a Duane Allman guitar solo, but he&#39;s perceptive when analyzing the musical approaches of the band&#39;s members, if you don&#39;t mind him lapsing into Guitar World argot: “Oakley played with an expansive, free-range mentality, like the Phil Lesh devotee he was, while Williams stayed more on the root and in the pocket.”</p><p> Phil Lesh was the bassist for the Grateful Dead, and the underexamined relationship between the Dead and the Allman Brothers is a major thread in this history. Although Macon and San Francisco are 2,500 miles away from each other, the two bands, each powered by a tandem of drummers and self-consciously balancing a fascination with American history against a modern counterculture sensibility, found themselves to be kindred spirits united by the liberating power of improvisation. The Dead and the Allmans shared top billing at some massive gigs, none bigger than the Summer Jam at Watkins Glen in 1973 (also featuring the Band), which drew 600,000 fans to upstate New York—bigger than Woodstock!—and landed the show in the Guinness Book of World Records.</p><p> The Allman Brothers leaned more heavily on the blues, while the Dead emphasized psychedelia and LSD. In the name of expanding minds, the Dead&#39;s entourage routinely dosed the backstage food and drinks of anyone they played with. “My drums started just drifting off into space,” Trucks said of a show his band shared with the Dead on New Year&#39;s Eve 1973. “When I could hit one it felt like hitting a marshmallow.”</p><p> For an impressionable teenager, the Allman Brothers could represent the adult world of rock &#39;n&#39; roll, a tantalizing garden of delights just out of reach. One particular teenager, Cameron Crowe, toured with the Allmans in 1973 as a 16-year-old writer for Rolling Stone. “We did a long, soulful, haunting interview in which [Gregg Allman] talked about missing his brother and the loneliness that he felt,” Mr. Crowe remembered. Then Allman commandeered Mr. Crowe&#39;s interview tapes—“I had their secrets in my orange bag and that freaked him out”—a moment that 27 years later inspired the central conflict in Mr. Crowe&#39;s autobiographical film “Almost Famous.”</p><p> During the band&#39;s heyday, its members lived on a farm in Georgia; when they emerged from that bucolic retreat, they intersected with the world of mainstream celebrity in unpredictable ways. The encounters provide some of the book&#39;s most entertaining passages. In his previous book, Mr. Paul barely mentioned the tale of Gregg Allman&#39;s 1975 marriage to then-superstar Cher: such a pop-culture event that Garry Trudeau did an extended storyline in the comic strip “Doonesbury” in which a disgruntled Uncle Duke (himself a thinly veiled caricature of Hunter S. Thompson) is appointed the Gregg-and-Cher bureau chief for Rolling Stone. Mr. Paul makes up for that omission here, not only by chronicling the major events relating to the couple (Cher filing for divorce nine days after they got married; their flop duo album, “Two the Hard Way,” credited to “Allman and Woman”) but also by detailing forgotten aspects of the relationship, such as the concomitant romance between Cher&#39;s assistant Paulette Eghiazarian and Allman&#39;s bandmate Dickey Betts.</p><p> The most surprising tale in “Brothers and Sisters” involves the friendship between Gregg Allman and Georgia Gov. Jimmy Carter,</p> forged over a late night at the governor&#39;s mansion in 1974 when they drank J&amp;B Scotch and listened to Elmore James records. Given the later travails of the Carter administration, it&#39;s easy to forget his groundbreaking appeal in the 1970s, when he was a new breed of American politician who could offhandedly quote both Reinhold Niebuhr and Bob Dylan. For a governor aspiring to the presidency of the United States, the Allman Brothers could help with the crucial youth vote and with fundraising via benefit gigs.<p></p><p> The Allman Brothers made their mark on American history in ways that extended beyond blowing the minds of fans by jamming on “Midnight Rider”: A band of outlaws and addicts discovered, rather to their surprise, that they wielded real political power. “The Allman Brothers helped put me in the White House by raising money when I didn&#39;t have any,” Mr. Carter later said. “If it hadn&#39;t been for Gregg Allman, I never would have been president.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Edwards&#39;s forthcoming book “MCU: The Reign of Marvel Studios,” co-authored with Joanna Robinson and Dave Gonzales, will be published in October.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:36:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brothers-and-sisters-review-the-age-of-the-allmans-956e44a4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brothers-and-sisters-review-the-age-of-the-allmans-956e44a4<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Fiction: ‘No One Prayed Over Their Graves’ by Khaled Khalifa]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Plus Andrew Ridker&#39;s &#39;Hope&#39; and Tessa Hadley&#39;s &#39;After the Funeral.&#39; <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590098212686324190"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818678?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Uncredited </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590098212686324190"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-sacks" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sam Sacks</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 11:26 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fiction-no-one-prayed-over-their-graves-by-khaled-khalifa-72bd9b4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> &#39;Why travel if all the world is coming to Aleppo, the capital of it all?” says a character in Khaled Khalifa&#39;s spacious historical novel “No One Prayed Over Their Graves.” This is the Aleppo of the Ottoman Empire at the turn of the 20th century, a teeming commercial entrepot and cross-cultural hub where Muslims, Christians and Jews fractiously but profitably coexisted. Set between 1881 and 1951 and following the waning fortunes of two families, the novel reads at times like a love letter to the Syrian city where Mr. Khalifa grew up, and at times like a eulogy. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a08fe83e-36d7-49f1-831b-d1c80323232e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> At its center are two privileged scions: Zakariya Bayazidi, the heir to a wealthy Muslim accountant, and Hanna Gregoros, who is adopted by the Bayazidis after his father is murdered in a pogrom targeting Syriac Christians. Early chapters glory in the boys&#39; hedonist youth hiding in brothels or stowing away to Paris. Hanna is the novel&#39;s true decadent and his masterpiece is the “citadel of pleasure,” a luxurious hideout guarded by a former prostitute that includes a platform from which visitors can commit suicide after a bad night of gambling. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The challenging science of human consciousness, watching history&#39;s cycles, the Allman Brothers&#39; Southern rock recipe and more.</p></div></div><p> Their turning point comes in 1907, when a flood from the Euphrates wipes out their ancestral village near Aleppo, killing their children and Hanna&#39;s wife. The river had not just taken his family, Hanna thinks, “it had drowned all his sordid and riotous past, his entire life.” He trades his pleasure palace for a monastery, becoming a barefoot ascetic, and the novel unfolds in the pale light of his and Zakariya&#39;s grief.</p><p> A gallery of side characters gives the book its amplitude. Mr. Khalifa includes texts purportedly written by Hanna to illuminate Aleppo&#39;s history, especially the devastating 1915 famine. And in the middle of everything, like a stand-alone novella, is a star-crossed romance involving Zakariya&#39;s childhood friend, a cultured young woman, and a wicked Ottoman official. Of the three books of Mr. Khalifa that I have read—“No Knives in the Kitchens of This City” is a furious chronicle of Aleppo under the Baathist dictatorship, and “Death Is Hard Work” a brilliant black comedy set during the ongoing civil war—this is the baggiest, the least concerned with pacing or plot.</p><p> It is, even so, a beautiful novel, and Mr. Khalifa&#39;s partnership with Leri Price is one of the most fruitful writer-translator pairings in literature today. The recent destruction of Aleppo provides unspoken context, charging the exploration of ruin and aftermath with further heartbreak. Gazing at the Euphrates after the flood, Hanna is dumbstruck by its calmness. Its “appearance was charming, innocent. The full moon reflected in the river, and absolute silence, utterly soundless, drowned the scene.” He waits for a miracle to emerge from its waters but sees only the melancholy flow of futurity. “One life had passed, and another went on.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/0a131049-bdef-4b25-b23b-07dbf0cc92cd.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Andrew Ridker&#39;s novel “Hope” begins in 2013 during the second term of the Obama presidency, and the ironic title gestures toward the fading promise of a once-galvanizing campaign slogan. The Greenspans are an outwardly model family in affluent Brookline, Mass., who, in private, are spectacularly imploding. Scott, a doctor, is caught fudging data on a clinical trial because he needs the funding to cover a bad investment. Deb, who in midlife has discovered an attraction to women, takes the opportunity to move in with her girlfriend, the domineering CEO of a charter-school academy. Their daughter, Maya, remains hung up on a loser English teacher from her high-school days, and their son, Gideon, has committed the ultimate offense to East Coast Jewish values by dropping out of college.</p><p> Mr. Ridker will need to take care to not become pigeonholed as a Jonathan Franzen copycat (unless this is his aim). As with his 2019 debut, “The Altruists,” one is constantly aware of the influence of “The Corrections” in the blending of suburban dysfunction with vague political topicality. But if “Hope” is less burdened by Mr. Franzen&#39;s Freudian hang-ups it&#39;s not always clear what it offers in their place. Humor is one fine quality. There is a funny opening scene of a dinner party awash with smarmy liberal pieties, and the book enlivens at every appearance of Scott&#39;s guilt-tripping mother, Marjorie, an outsize figure who has crashed through caricature and come out the other side. The other Greenspans seem faceless in comparison, believably defined but never fully realized. “Hope” has the commendable trappings of a big, meaty family novel but lacks the heft and vision to meet its ambition. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a63e5622-9b8e-4d35-8daa-af7b8b7701f3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “After the Funeral” is Tessa Hadley&#39;s 12th book and fourth story collection. To call it excellent would be true but uninteresting, given her nearly unerring track record. More worthwhile is to use the collection to investigate just how this superb writer&#39;s fiction works.</p><p> One surprise, perhaps, is its reliance on archetypes. In “The Bunty Club,” “My Mother&#39;s Wedding” and the title story, Ms. Hadley establishes conflict in domestic arrangements by throwing together clashing personalities—a hippie and a pragmatist, for instance, or a sensualist and a bookworm. Yet within these general categories the characters are wonderfully individualized. In “Coda,” the mousy daughter who has moved back home during lockdown spends all morning fixing her elegant, thrice-married mother&#39;s hair into a chiffon, whereas her own hair has grown hopelessly “into long lumps like spaniel ears.”</p><p> Then there&#39;s the signature Hadley maneuver: the abrupt point-of-view shift to reveal events from a different angle, best illustrated here in “Cecilia Awakened.” Cecilia is a loving only child in a close-knit family, but during a trip to Florence when she is 15 she becomes suddenly uncomfortable in her body and embarrassed by her parents. “Writh[ing] with consciousness,” she finds dark meanings in the Renaissance paintings she is certain they don&#39;t grasp . 。 。 and then the narrative jumps to the thoughts of her mother, transported to her own memories of forlorn adolescence. The story ends, like so many of Ms. Hadley&#39;s, with a moment of intense insight and recognition.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fiction-no-one-prayed-over-their-graves-by-khaled-khalifa-72bd9b4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fiction-no-one-prayed-over-their-graves-by-khaled-khalifa-72bd9b4<author><![CDATA[Sam Sacks]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Voices of Nature’ Review: Calls of the Wild]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Animals may not have languages approaching human speech, but their cries, grunts, howls and squeaks are often surprisingly meaningful. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590096543273278652"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821085?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A pair of young spectacled caimans.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Aldo Brando/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590096543273278652"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">David P. Barash</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 11:18 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-voices-of-nature-review-calls-of-the-wild-cfaa4c38"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> From King Solomon&#39;s ring to Doctor Dolittle, humans have been fascinated with the prospect of talking to the animals, or, failing that, eavesdropping as they talk to one another. There may be more children&#39;s picture books with talking critters than picture books with conversing people. “The Voices of Nature: How and Why Animals Communicate” isn&#39;t for children, but it is a multifaceted delight for animal-lovers and armchair adventurers. Nicolas Mathevon, a professor at the University of Saint-Etienne in France, is one of the world&#39;s most prolific researchers in bioacoustics. If you want to know what African striped mice say to one another when they&#39;re alone together, his book is the book for you. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/48d13ec9-73b8-4eb4-a4a3-07f3ad5749e5.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Ludwig Wittgenstein famously wrote that “If a lion could speak, we could not understand him,” because our frames of reference would be so different. Can we truly understand what animals are saying, chirping, singing, calling, barking, growling, warbling, whistling? Maybe not precisely, but as Mr. Mathevon shows, it&#39;s scientifically possible to try. Wittgenstein might be surprised at how much we can in fact discern: There are evident meaning of variations in frequency, intensity, pattern, and the like.</p><p> The author relies on simple, easy-to-grasp field experiments to show, for example, whether members of a given species recognize one another as individuals and whether complex semantic information is encoded in animal language. A now-famous example of the latter comes from African vervet monkeys, which produce three alarm calls: “a first (&#39;kof&#39;) for leopard-like land predators; a second (&#39;uaho&#39;) for aerial predators like the martial eagle, and a third &#39;(&#39;cla-clack . . . cla-clack&#39;) for snakes.” Responses are different in each case: “They climb a tree when they hear the leopard call. When it is an eagle call, they look to the sky and hide under the nearest bush. And in response to the snake call, the adults stand up on their hind legs and scan the ground, grouping together to harry the trespasser.”</p><p> Other chapters present fascinating puzzles, such as how parents and offspring identify one another, especially when breeding in dense seabird or bat colonies of thousands, even millions of pairs. Since such breeding colonies are remarkably noisy, success requires increasing the signal-to-noise ratio. Parent-offspring communication in general receives a great deal of attention in “The Voices of Nature,” which includes a fascinating account of how birds that are regularly victimized by nest parasites such as cuckoos teach their legitimate offspring a password by employing an “incubation call” while the chicks are still inside their eggs. After hatching: no password? No food. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The challenging science of human consciousness, watching history&#39;s cycles, the Allman Brothers&#39; Southern rock recipe and more.</p></div></div><p> Readers learn about the “dear enemy effect,” whereby animals that “own” a territory may act blasé about vocalizations from their neighbors, with whom they have a stable relationship, but are greatly agitated by a new vocal calling card, indicating an intruder. Yet in animal communication, as in human speech, mix-ups often happen: A hyena who identifies a colleague by its giggle doesn&#39;t necessarily recognize the same individual by its whoop.</p><p> Male superb lyrebirds regularly practice intentional miscommunication—some would say deception—ventriloquizing to give the impression that a dangerous predator is nearby. This includes adjusting vocalizations to make it seem that many different birds are harassing the nonexistent predator, superimposing calls of several species and even adding fake sounds of flapping wings. This vocal tour-de-force is emitted only while mating, during which the male perches on the female and waves his wings in front of her, blocking her view and reinforcing the illusion that moving away would be dangerous.</p><p> How do humpback whales sing their famous songs without pushing air through their throats or blowholes? I won&#39;t tell you, but Mr. Mathevon does. His carefully documented research also silences anyone who questions whether animals recognize one another as individuals. Such vocal signatures shouldn&#39;t be surprising given that we take for granted our own ability to identify people, or pets, by their voices.</p><p> The author&#39;s enthusiasm for his subject is evident and contagious, but can sometimes be overdone. I&#39;ve never read a book of expository science laden with exclamation marks. “Most insects cannot hear anything!” “Koalas have a second vocal organ!” Ironically, for a book that masterfully guides the reader through tactics of communication, many of its paragraphs are intimidatingly long, often occupying a whole page. But “The Voices of Nature” offers more than enough in recompense for these stylistic tics—including an up-close seat to Mr. Mathevon&#39;s intrepid adventures in the field.</p><p> The field experiments the author recounts take place among free-living animals all over the world, Arctic to Antarctic, underwater to rainforest canopies. He wondered whether female crocodiles can hear their unhatched but vocal young while the eggs are buried under sand. So he recorded their sounds, buried a speaker, did a playback and found out. (Spoiler: They do.) He similarly showed that baby black caimans (South American relatives of alligators) have contact calls that keep the brood together as well as distress calls that “enrage” the mother. Given that adult black caimans can be up to 20 feet long and weigh 1,000 pounds—and are known to eat jaguars, anacondas and humans—it takes a lot of scientific commitment to enrage one in the wild.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Barash is professor emeritus of psychology at the University of Washington. His latest book is “Oops! The Worst Blunders of All Time, from Pandora&#39;s Box to Putin&#39;s War.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-voices-of-nature-review-calls-of-the-wild-cfaa4c38</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-voices-of-nature-review-calls-of-the-wild-cfaa4c38<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>natural environment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘History’s Angel’ Review: Dreaming of an India for All]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In Anjum Hasan&#39;s novel, a mild-mannered Delhi teacher turns to history to understand an increasingly perilous present. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093852202035796"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820651?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The 17th-century Delhi citadel known as the Red Fort, commissioned by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Danny Lehman/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590093852202035796"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Anna Mundow</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 11:11 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/historys-angel-fiction-review-dreaming-of-an-india-for-all-8f7d591d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Picture for a moment that consummate daydreamer Walter Mitty, transplanted from Waterbury, Conn., to Delhi, India, and there you have Alif Mohammad, the hero of Anjum Hasan&#39;s novel “History&#39;s Angel.” At least at first glance. For Alif, like Mitty, is mild-mannered and easily distracted. The sight of bread left out to nourish the city&#39;s strays, for example, prompts him to wonder if “this was how it felt to walk the streets in the third or fourth century . 。 。 when, under the influence of the gentle creeds of Buddhism and Jainism, emperors patronised dispensaries for sick animals.” Which in turn leads him to contemplate the many Mughals who revered wild creatures, unlike the British who favored “administering with the sword and decimating wildlife with the gun.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/59a8cd7d-2bbe-4a8b-b88a-fadec5aabffe.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Breaking through Alif&#39;s mental cloud, meanwhile, are texts from his wife: “U hv to help me with my asgment on sales strategising, rmber?” He has, of course, forgotten but hurries home because he loves his clever and ambitious Tahira, just as he loves his teenage son, Salim, though both—as habitués of the modern world—occasionally mystify him. “They&#39;re smart, these two,” he marvels, as mother and son tackle questions for her business college course. “They have built a raft out of such devilish fictions to stay afloat in the barbaric present.” While Alif remains enchanted by the past, more specifically the history of his country, ancient and modern, which he teaches—much to his school principal&#39;s annoyance—in all its tantalizing complexity.</p><p> “I would like them to see that India is not any one thing,” he argues when reprimanded for his unorthodox approach, “with any one obvious destiny.” Sniffing treason, Mrs. Rawat, “who counts herself among the nation&#39;s guardians,” sternly advises Alif to stick to the approved version of Indian identity. Never mind this infatuation with a distant golden age “of cross-connections, [of] cultures and religions mingling.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The challenging science of human consciousness, watching history&#39;s cycles, the Allman Brothers&#39; Southern rock recipe and more.</p></div></div><p> Talk of past tolerance is not only officially discouraged, Alif soon learns, it is also unwise at a time when Hindu-Muslim animosities are growing. And as anti-Muslim rhetoric intensifies in Alif&#39;s own neighborhood, even friends and family begin to lose patience with his historical perspective. Who wants to learn about the 19th-century Delhi Renaissance, after all, when the nightly news is warning of blood in the streets? “Things are bad,” an elderly aunt protests. “They are hounding us. They are finding excuses to kill us.” To which Alif&#39;s father replies, “When was any of this new?”</p><p> Detonations remain muffled in this wonderfully restrained, shrewdly comic novel, yet even the smallest shock reverberates. A fourth-grade pupil provokes Alif to near-violence with a religious insult and later, in a particularly effective scene, he and Tahira encounter far more sophisticated abuse when viewing an apartment owned by a Hindu landlord: “If we&#39;d stood there a minute longer, he&#39;d have stripped me down,” Tahira fumes afterward to her husband. “He asked me if I bring dead animals to the house. He asked me why I wear what I wear. Weren&#39;t you listening?” Alif was listening. To “the madness of the centuries,” as he puts it, though he wisely keeps this observation to himself.</p><p> Condemned to be the voice of reason in the most unreasonable of times, Alif might also have become a mere symbol in this novel: “History&#39;s Angel” indeed. But Ms. Hasan grants this hero such a complete inner life—and surrounds him with such finely drawn characters—that the very air he breathes seems dense with thoughts and longings. The reappearance of a girl from Alif&#39;s past, for example, turns him briefly into a lovesick teenager. At other times, he indulges in nostalgia for his childhood, “not because things were better then, but because he misses the predominant colour of those years, a washed-out yellow. He doesn&#39;t know where it comes from, that pale cast of his memory—maybe the old pages of the <em>Illustrated Weekly of India</em> .” In rare moments of solitude, Alif even tries, unsuccessfully, “to recover that long-ago feeling called God.”</p><p> Alif&#39;s dwindling elders, for their part, still suffer the alienation and yearning bequeathed on them by the 1947 Partition of India. “I made the big journey,” one man recalls, capturing a monumental tragedy in five simple words. “You never saw the streets of Lahore again,” echoes his wife. Her own story was more fortunate, because her native city, Amritsar, “did not go there but stayed here,” as Alif dryly observes of the “grand mess . 。 。 of 1947,” which consigned to the newly created state of Pakistan cities more ancient than any manmade border.</p><p> There is as much history, then, in this quiet novel as there is in any sweeping epic by Amitav Ghosh. And as much tension—between the fading past and the frenzied present—as there is in Aravind Adiga&#39;s “The White Tiger.” But “History&#39;s Angel” has none of Mr. Adiga&#39;s wildness or bite. Its charm lies instead in its mildness. In the tradition of RK Narayan and VS Naipaul, among other masters, Ms. Hasan casts the frail net of memory on a sea of historic events to come up with the muddied truth. For though “the past always seems simple from a distance,” Alif has learned “it is full of inexhaustibly interesting mysteries.” Take the Byzantines, for example, a civilization so advanced “that we cannot quite grasp it yet because ours, more than a thousand years on, is so retrograde.”</p><p> Retrograde or not, the quotidian world of Delhi, “the city on which the apocalypse descends every day,” is conjured up by Ms. Hasan with acuity and palpable affection. As is the domestic realm to which Alif can only surrender. Tahira strives for a higher management job; Salim dreams of becoming a high-tech hotshot; a rich cousin urges Alif to ditch teaching and take over his shoe boutique. And even our cloud-dwelling hero, while pondering the Byzantines among others, is drawn back inexorably to the turmoil in his father&#39;s house, for example, or thoughts of the girl from his past, now middle-aged like him. But resigned to reality, unlike him. For Alif will always be one who “loves the <em>idea</em> of ideas.” And who loves India—whatever that is, as he might say.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em>Ms. Mundow is a writer in central Massachusetts.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/historys-angel-fiction-review-dreaming-of-an-india-for-all-8f7d591d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/historys-angel-fiction-review-dreaming-of-an-india-for-all-8f7d591d<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Schoenberg’ Review: Hard to Like, Impossible to Ignore]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The composer created barbed, difficult music based on revolutionary ideas. Appreciating its power takes practice. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590092603739146046"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820656?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Arnold Schoenberg.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Smith Archive/Alamy </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590092603739146046"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Tim Page</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 11:08 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/schoenberg-review-hard-to-like-impossible-to-ignore-99e96580"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Harvey Sachs has been among our most significant and persuasive writers about music for some 50 years, with a dozen books to his credit. His subjects have ranged from Beethoven&#39;s Ninth Symphony to the pianist Arthur Rubinstein to the musical world of fascist Italy. In 2017, he produced his masterpiece to date, “Toscanini: Musician of Conscience”—almost a thousand pages long and thrilling in its narrative sweep and command of historical detail. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/cd406023-1b2e-4709-8ca4-d11d21f2a42f.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> By comparison, Mr. Sachs&#39;s “Schoenberg: Why He Matters” is a model of concision—a concentrated meditation instead of a panorama. It may be recommended for anybody with an interest in the work of the Viennese-American composer Arnold Schoenberg—and perhaps especially to those who have never quite been able to “crack” his music.</p><p> Mr. Sachs states at the outset that he is not trying to convince his readers that any vast new public awaits Schoenberg&#39;s work. To the contrary: “Now that atonality and the twelve-tone technique (and its offshoots) have been with us for a century we may safely say that they have proved to be dead ends for most listeners and for many—perhaps even most—professional performing musicians as well.”</p><p> But this should not be taken as a dismissal. For a number of indisputable geniuses, the audience may not be large, but it is intelligent, passionate and devoted. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e" target="_blank" class="icon none">14 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/14-books-we-read-this-week-eb82ff8e"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815740?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The challenging science of human consciousness, watching history&#39;s cycles, the Allman Brothers&#39; Southern rock recipe and more.</p></div></div><p> Only a few of Schoenberg&#39;s pieces have made it into the standard concert repertory. The reason for the popularity of these works is simple: Schoenberg&#39;s youthful compositions—“Transfigured Night,” above all—are written in the late Romantic manner of Wagner and Strauss and will not befuddle unaccustomed listeners. And the massive “Gurrelieder” holds a proud place among the grandly exuberant, evening-length choral works that greeted the early years of the 20th century, ranking with Mahler&#39;s Eighth Symphony and Elgar&#39;s “The Kingdom.”</p><p> But Schoenberg&#39;s style changed radically after 1910. “Pierrot Lunaire” (1912), a cycle of 21 terse songs written for a vocalist who half-sings, half-speaks the words, sounded rather like cabaret music for Martians. It was a radical and fascinating piece, but even one of Schoenberg&#39;s most fervent American disciples, the late composer Charles Wuorinen, noted that “listening to it occasionally reminds one of attempts to befriend a porcupine.”</p><p> Much of Schoenberg&#39;s music is difficult, for both listener and performer. Of the Violin Concerto, completed in 1936, Jascha Heifetz reportedly told Schoenberg that “in order to play it he would have to grow a sixth finger on his left hand,” Mr. Sachs writes.</p><p> Mr. Sachs goes on to speak of his own experience with the concerto: “I confess that I failed to grasp either its importance or its hidden beauties until I heard Hilary Hahn&#39;s extraordinary recording of it, which conveys its delicacy as well as its power. Even then, however, and after having studied the printed score, I had to listen to the piece multiple times in order to shed my initial hostility toward it.”</p><p> Such personal asides are welcome: They give a reader the sense that a brilliant teacher is not only leading us through the music but discovering it once more for himself. Mr. Sachs endorses his favorite performances (he prefers the LaSalle Quartet&#39;s recordings of the chamber music); admits his disappointment with “Transfigured Night” and explains the reasons for it; and examines the composer&#39;s curious attempt to write a short comic opera, “Von heute auf Morgen,” which was so dour and clotted that it received only two performances during Schoenberg&#39;s lifetime. (Listening to it, one recalls Mark Twain&#39;s purported comment: “A German joke is no laughing matter.”)</p><p> Schoenberg could be a cantankerous man. “Convinced of his own genius and of the supreme urgency of his needs over all other considerations,” Mr. Sachs writes, “he was high-strung, often irascible, prone to mood swings, and, according to some (although not all) of his acquaintances during the early part of his career, sometimes given to excessive drinking.” A household employee spoke of a “negative, aggressive atmosphere in the Schoenberg house, very turbulent with permanent quarrels.”</p><p> His heritage was Jewish, and he fled Berlin to California upon the rise of Nazism in the early 1930s. He never returned to Europe again. But Schoenberg remained fiercely committed to the supposed “supremacy” of German music and claimed that his “teachers” were “primarily Bach and Mozart and secondarily Beethoven, Brahms and Wagner.”</p><p> Mr. Sachs calls out such snobbery: “Never mind the fact that Bach and (especially) Mozart had learned a great deal from their Italian elders and contemporaries; never mind that Schoenberg admired Tchaikovsky&#39;s mastery of orchestration, or that, in later years, he kept the scores of Verdi&#39;s <em>Otello</em> and <em>Falstaff</em> in his study: for him, the terms &#39;great music&#39; and &#39;great German music&#39; were virtually interchangeable.” Schoenberg admitted that foreigners were capable of writing “enjoyable, even brilliant music,” as Mr. Sachs puts it, but the “great, deep works were German.” Schoenberg once wrote that he would have liked his music to be as popular as Tchaikovsky&#39;s, but of course, as Mr. Sachs observes, “Tchaikovsky&#39;s music couldn&#39;t have been as profound as his own! Tchaikovsky was Russian; Schoenberg was German.”</p><p> For several decades after World War II, the history of musical modernism in the first half of the 20th century was often presented as some sort of righteous, titanic struggle between the paths laid down by Schoenberg and Igor Stravinsky. (After Schoenberg&#39;s death, Stravinsky adopted some aspects of the older man&#39;s compositional theories.) It was a preposterously limiting choice, and many of the composers who now mean a great deal to younger musicians—Richard Strauss and Jean Sibelius in particular—were generally ignored or dismissed as reactionaries.</p><p> Despite his postwar decades in California, Schoenberg—with his rattles and shimmers, his craggy melodies and pervasive angst—never quite escaped the nightmares of what was then a crabbed and bloody Old World. At his least appealing, Schoenberg reminds us of a passing stranger who shakes our lapels and tells us what a terrible day he is having. Yet he gave us some great music, and, if he no longer seems any sort of universal sage, he remains a powerful and far-reaching figure. Mr. Sachs&#39;s fine study should inspire a fresh understanding of his life and work.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Page is a professor emeritus of musicology at the University of Southern California and the author of “Parallel Play” and “Dawn Powell: A Biography.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 15:08:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/schoenberg-review-hard-to-like-impossible-to-ignore-99e96580</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/schoenberg-review-hard-to-like-impossible-to-ignore-99e96580<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>